            <h6 type="button" data-toggle="modal" data-target="#myblogs1">
            	Unsuccessful Hallucination (My attempt to see Nowise comet)
            </h6>
<div class="modal fade" id="myblogs1" tabindex="-1" aria-labelledby="exampleModalLabel" aria-hidden="true">
  <div class="modal-dialog">
    <div class="modal-content">
      <div class="modal-header">
        <h5 class="modal-title" id="exampleModalLabel">Unsuccessful Hallucination (My attempt to see Nowise comet)</h5>
        <button type="button" class="close" data-dismiss="modal" aria-label="Close">
          <span aria-hidden="true">&times;</span>
        </button>
      </div>
      <div class="modal-body">
        <img src="\pics\pic1.jpg" style="width: 100%;"><br><hr>
<b>There’s</b> always an astronomer hidden inside all of us wondering what is there inside the stars or galaxies, as a science student I can explain all of this but imagination is also a thing here. So, once I read somewhere about the comet called Nowise, passing some 64 million miles from our planet and will be again in sight after 6700 years, also can be seen through our naked eyes. I mean a comet I can observe while sitting on my roof. It is once in a lifetime opportunity. So I searched about it and the location where it ought to be seen and waited for the time when it is actually in sight, maybe mid of July. They said it would be seen in early morning just before sunrise and just after the sunset at the time interval of twenty minutes or so. <br><br>
On 17th of July at 6:30 pm with my younger brother, leave the town to have the maximum glimpse of a comet. The weather was hazy and sky is partially covered with clouds. Somewhere I got the idea that today I could not see it, but there’s also a hope. We reached to a fine spot away from the city lights and there is still a time left for perfect hue of evening. For that purpose I already had downloaded comet app for locating the comets. So on dragging my phone to that direction, guess what we have found. Clouds, a big chunk of cloud seems to be making fun of us. We waited for half an hour but can’t see it, and at last taking our hopes to ground we went back. <br><br>
Another day, another dusk, I decided to go again, and made my friends agree to come along. But again clouds ditched us, we ate patties and went back home. For day or two the cycle continues, than on 22nd of July the day comes when it is nearest to earth. And I know today is the day, so what I did, can you guess? I didn’t go there. Don’t know why, but my mind had accepted the fact that I cannot see it. Or I am being totally subjugated by my prior attempts that made me uninterested to see it again. The journey of thoughts, so much consumed by posting its picture on my Insta feed to genuinely uninterested to even get a little glimpse, ended here, right in this blog. <br><br>
I hope someone is also trying hard to say hi to Nowise, they even say that comets are the old souls wandering in this infinite universe. May be sometime my fate get struck and I could also have the chance to see it. It’s all hallucination.
