            <h6 type="button" data-toggle="modal" data-target="#myblogs5">
            	Steve Jobs by Walter Isaacson (Book Review)
            </h6>
<div class="modal fade" id="myblogs5" tabindex="-1" aria-labelledby="exampleModalLabel" aria-hidden="true">
  <div class="modal-dialog">
    <div class="modal-content">
      <div class="modal-header">
        <h5 class="modal-title" id="exampleModalLabel">Steve Jobs by Walter Isaacson (Book Review)</h5>
        <button type="button" class="close" data-dismiss="modal" aria-label="Close">
          <span aria-hidden="true">&times;</span>
        </button>
      </div>
      <div class="modal-body">
There are some biographies which inspires you so legit to being that man. This book, a biography of a Silicon Valley magnus, Steve Jobs, takes you to another world of smart minded people working there sweat off on amazing ideas. If you read it, then it is sure that you will be mesmerized by his personality, the passion and that dazzling impatience in the eyes. The whole story, in fact each phase of his life is revolved around innovation and inventions creating a burning desire to develop impossible. <br><br>
If you mix consistency and ideas with a pinch of art in it using the ratio perfectly, then an Apple product is born. The perfectness which excites Jobs creates the huge difference in Apple and other competitive brands. The book shows that if you work on your ideas and believe in your efforts than anything is possible. The favorite part of the book was when the first iPhone is launched, the whole strategy they make to assemble and built its parts, and then the final launch event. The whole crowd was excited to see the new product and Jobs came on stage and announced that now everything is possible on a single device and it is in his pocket. The lights focused there and he took out a slick black device, an iPhone. Everyone went crazy all over the world when they saw iPhone, the coolest gadget ever launched and it made the Apple a benchmark brand. <br><br>
<b>Gates and Jobs, When Orbits Intersect</b> <br><br>
It is my favorite chapter of the book, which still gives me goose bumps. Everyone had heard about the famous rivalry between Microsoft and Apple about the products they created and their operating system UI. For the first thirty years of the personal computer age, beginning in the late 1970s, the defining binary star system was composed of two high-energy college dropouts both born in 1955. <br><br>
Gates was good at computer coding and his mind was more practical, disciplined, and abundant in analytic processing power, unlike Jobs. Who is more intuitive and had a greater instinct for making technology usable, design delightful, and interfaces friendly. He had a passion for perfection, which made him fiercely demanding. They have to collide at some point of their life and the time comes when they build the similar OS containing lookalike user interface. Jobs argued about the design for the UI to be his idea and the debate then created into something big topic of history. <br><br>
The book ultimately is a journey you will never want to miss. For technology enthusiasts and those who followed Steve Jobs’s life as though he were Bob Dylan, the biography reinforces the previously known timeline to be its major ingredent. To make your day, Job’s quote for the first ad of an Apple.
“Here’s to the crazy ones, the misfits, the rebels, the troublemakers, the round pegs in the square holes… the ones who see things differently - they’re not fond of rules… You can quote them, disagree with them, glorify or vilify them, but the only thing you can’t do is ignore them because they change things… they push the human race forward, and while some may see them as the crazy ones, we see genius, because the ones who are crazy enough to think that they can change the world, are the ones who do.”
